results.name: a(n) = number of exponents occurring only once each in the prime factorization of n!.
example: 14! is factored into primes as 2^11 * 3^5 * 5^2 * 7^2 * 11^1 * 13^1. The exponent 1 and 2 each occur more than once. So the exponents occurring only once each are 5 and 11. Therefore a(14) = 2.
maple: A133924 := proc(n) local ifs,a,i ; if n <= 1 then RETURN(0) ; else ifs := ifactors(n!)[2] ; ifs := sort([seq(op(2,i),i=ifs)]) ; a :=0 ; for i from 1 to nops(ifs) do if i = 1 or op(i,ifs) <> op(i-1,ifs) then if i=nops(ifs) or op(i,ifs) <> op(i+1,ifs) then a := a+1 ; fi ; fi ; od: RETURN(a) ; fi ; end: seq(A133924(n),n=0..120) ; # _R. J. Mathar_, Jan 30 2008
